    <p>All three platforms cover the foundational elements of privacy compliance, but each prioritizes different capabilities within policy generation, consent management, and automation tooling. iubenda bundles the widest feature set under a single subscription, while Termly emphasizes U.S.-focused policy generators and Osano concentrates on enterprise privacy management workflows.</p>

    <h3>Policy Generation Capabilities</h3>
    <p>iubenda includes a <strong>privacy policy generator</strong>, <strong>cookie policy generator</strong>, and <strong>terms and conditions generator</strong> across most paid tiers. The policy generators support 27 languages and update automatically when regulations change. You can customize clauses for specific data processors, third-party integrations, and regional laws without drafting text from scratch.</p>
    <p>Termly also offers policy generators for privacy policies, cookie policies, and terms of service. The templates focus on U.S. laws such as CCPA and CalOPPA alongside GDPR requirements. Customization options are more limited compared to iubenda's multi-language library, and the tooling skews toward small businesses operating primarily in North America.</p>
    <p>Osano does not include built-in policy generators. Teams using Osano typically rely on separate vendors or legal counsel to draft privacy policies and terms of conditions, which adds coordination overhead and additional contracts to manage.</p>

    <h3>Consent Management Platform</h3>
    <p>All three vendors operate as <strong>consent management platforms</strong> (CMPs). iubenda's CMP is IAB-validated for the Transparency &amp; Consent Framework (TCF 2.3) and certified by Google as a CMP Partner with Consent Mode integration. The platform includes geo-targeting, granular consent categories, and consent recovery tools designed to optimize opt-in rates without forcing compliance.</p>
    <p>Termly provides a consent management solution with basic banner customization and geo-rules for GDPR and CCPA. The CMP lacks advanced features such as consent paywalls or built-in analytics for tracking banner performance against site metrics.</p>
    <p>Osano's <strong>privacy management</strong> approach includes a CMP with stronger enterprise workflows — vendor risk assessments, <strong>internal privacy management</strong> dashboards, and integration hooks for larger compliance stacks. Setup typically requires developer time or professional services, making it less suitable for smaller teams without dedicated GRC resources.</p>

    <h3>Compliance Automation Tools</h3>
    <p>iubenda's <strong>compliance scanning</strong> includes an automated <a href="/cookieyes-review.html">cookie scanner</a> that inventories trackers across your domain, rebuilds the cookie list when scripts change, and flags unregistered third-party tags. The platform also bundles <strong>compliance solutions</strong> such as data subject access request (DSAR) workflow management, a register of processing activities (ROPA), whistleblowing intake, and an accessibility widget aligned with the European Accessibility Act.</p>
    <p>Termly includes a cookie scanner as part of its <strong>compliance software</strong> offering but does not extend into DSAR automation, whistleblowing, or accessibility tooling. Teams needing those capabilities must contract additional vendors.</p>
    <p>Osano focuses scanning and automation on cookie and tracker detection, vendor assessments, and consent record retention. The platform integrates with enterprise systems for internal privacy management but does not offer a native accessibility module or whistleblowing portal.</p>

    <h2>Cookie Consent Solutions and Banners</h2>

    <div class="video-embed">
      <iframe width="100%" height="400" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/LHDtVoQnkCU" title="Cookie Consent Overview" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen loading="lazy"></iframe>
    </div>

    <p>All three platforms deliver cookie consent banners with automated scanning and customization options, though they differ in depth of control and ease of setup.</p>

    <h3>Cookie Banner Customization</h3>
    <p>iubenda offers extensive customization through its Google-certified consent banner, supporting over 10 languages natively with options to adjust layout, colors, and messaging to match your brand identity. The platform provides pre-built templates that you can modify without coding knowledge.</p>
    <p>Termly delivers customizable cookie consent banners through a guided setup process designed for beginners. You can adjust banner placement, styling, and text content through their dashboard, though the free plan limits some customization features. The Pro+ plan unlocks custom branding options for a more tailored appearance.</p>
    <p>Osano provides consent banner customization through an intuitive interface, but users report that customization options are more limited compared to other platforms. The banners support basic color and text modifications, with advanced styling features gated behind higher-tier plans starting at $199/month.</p>

    <h3>Automated Cookie Scanning</h3>
    <p>iubenda includes an automated site scanner that detects cookies and trackers across your website, organizing them by category and maintaining an up-to-date cookie policy generator. The scanner runs regularly to catch new cookies as your site evolves, with first-party cookie mapping included.</p>
    <p>Termly's cookie scanner automatically identifies and categorizes cookies on your site, blocking them until user consent is obtained. The free plan covers up to 10,000 monthly pageviews with unlimited scans available on paid tiers. The scanner integrates directly with the cookie consent manager for streamlined compliance.</p>
    <p>Osano automates cookie detection and classification through regular scans, maintaining real-time updates in your dashboard. The scanner identifies cookies from third-party vendors and tracks changes, though some users note the scanning frequency is less customizable than competing platforms.</p>

    <h3>Cookie Consent Management</h3>
    <p>iubenda centralizes consent tracking through a unified dashboard where you manage user preferences, consent logs, and cookie policies. The platform integrates with Google Consent Mode and Tag Manager, storing consent records to demonstrate compliance with GDPR and CCPA requirements.</p>
    <p>Termly combines its cookie consent banner with automatic blocking capabilities, ensuring cookies don't load until users provide consent. The platform includes built-in privacy policy and cookie policy generators, maintaining consent records accessible through your account dashboard. DSAR tools help you respond to user data requests.</p>
    <p>Osano's consent management system tracks user preferences across sessions and provides detailed consent logs with timestamps. The platform automates consent enforcement and includes vendor risk monitoring, backed by their "No Fines, No Penalties" pledge covering regulatory fines up to $500,000.</p>

    <h2>Privacy Law Coverage and Compliance</h2>

    <div class="video-embed">
      <iframe width="100%" height="400" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Ejr7F6iVYuE" title="Privacy Law Coverage" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen loading="lazy"></iframe>
    </div>

    <p>All three platforms support GDPR and CCPA, but they differ in how deeply they handle specific requirements like ePrivacy Directive cookie rules, CPRA's sensitive data categories, and emerging laws like Brazil's LGPD.</p>

    <h3>GDPR and ePrivacy Directive</h3>
    <p>iubenda offers the most granular GDPR compliance tools among the three. It provides automated privacy policy generation that covers GDPR's Article 13 and 14 transparency requirements, plus built-in support for the ePrivacy Directive's cookie consent rules. The platform automatically updates policies when EU regulations change and includes consent receipts that log user choices with timestamps.</p>
    <p>Termly handles GDPR basics well for small businesses. Its cookie consent banners block trackers before consent, meeting ePrivacy Directive standards. However, customization options are more limited compared to iubenda, and the free plan doesn't include all GDPR-required features like automatic policy updates.</p>
    <p>Osano goes beyond standard GDPR compliance by adding vendor risk monitoring. This helps you track third-party processors required under GDPR Article 28. The platform also covers ePrivacy cookie consent requirements and backs its GDPR tools with legal assurance through its "No Fines, No Penalties" pledge up to $500,000.</p>

    <h3>CCPA and CPRA Support</h3>
    <p>All three platforms support CCPA compliance, including "Do Not Sell My Personal Information" disclosures and opt-out mechanisms. iubenda and Osano both updated their tools to handle CPRA's expanded requirements, including sensitive personal information categories and the right to limit use.</p>
    <p>Termly offers CCPA-ready privacy policies and consent management at lower price points. The platform includes data subject access request (DSAR) workflows for handling California consumer rights requests. However, CPRA-specific features like sensitive data handling are less detailed than what Osano provides.</p>
    <p>Osano stands out with dedicated CPRA compliance tools that categorize sensitive personal information automatically. Its DSAR automation handles the full range of California privacy rights, including correction and deletion requests.</p>

    <h3>LGPD and International Laws</h3>
    <p>iubenda leads in international privacy law coverage. The platform supports Brazil's LGPD, South Africa's POPIA, Canada's PIPEDA, and multiple other data protection frameworks. Policy generators include country-specific clauses, and the consent management system adapts to different legal requirements automatically.</p>
    <p>Termly covers LGPD basics but focuses primarily on US and EU regulations. International law support is less comprehensive, making it better suited for businesses operating mainly in North America and Europe.</p>
    <p>Osano provides LGPD compliance tools and tracks regulatory updates across multiple jurisdictions. The platform's vendor risk features help manage international data transfers required under LGPD Article 33 and similar provisions in other laws.</p>

    <h2>Platform Usability and Customization</h2>

    <h3>Ease of Use and Setup</h3>
    <p>Termly delivers the most streamlined onboarding experience. You can deploy a cookie banner and generate privacy policies in minutes without technical knowledge. The interface guides you through each step with clear prompts.</p>
    <p>iubenda requires slightly more configuration but compensates with a well-organized dashboard. You'll need to map your cookies and adjust settings manually, though the process remains straightforward for most users. The platform provides detailed documentation to help you navigate setup.</p>
    <p>Osano sits between the two. The initial deployment is quick, but accessing advanced features like vendor risk monitoring demands more time. The dashboard layout is intuitive, though some users report that finding specific settings can take extra clicks compared to Termly's simplified navigation.</p>

    <h3>Multi-Language Support</h3>
    <p>Among these three platforms, iubenda leads with support for over 12 languages in its consent banners and policy generators. This makes it particularly valuable if you operate in multiple European markets or serve diverse audiences.</p>
    <p>Termly offers multi-language support on paid plans, covering the most common languages including English, Spanish, French, German, and Italian. The free plan limits you to English-only banners.</p>
    <p>Osano provides multi-language consent management as well, though the language count falls behind iubenda. You'll find adequate coverage for major markets, but smaller regional languages may not be available.</p>

    <h3>Templates and Personalization</h3>
    <p>iubenda provides the most granular customization options. You can adjust banner layout, button placement, color schemes, and messaging while maintaining compliance standards. Policy templates are modular, letting you add or remove clauses based on your specific data practices.</p>
    <p>Termly focuses on simplicity with pre-built templates that work out of the box. Customization options exist but are more limited on the free plan. Paid plans unlock custom branding, advanced styling, and the ability to modify policy language.</p>
    <p>Osano offers functional templates with moderate customization. You can adjust colors and basic layout elements, though users note that banner design options feel more restricted compared to iubenda's flexibility. The platform prioritizes compliance over extensive visual customization.</p>

