    <h3>Starting Price Comparison</h3>
    <p>iubenda's entry-level paid plan costs €4.99/month (approximately $5.30) for up to 25,000 pageviews with no restrictions on users or domains. Termly requires an annual subscription with its paid tier starting around $10/month when billed annually. Osano's first paid tier starts at $199/month for 30,000 visitors, capped at 2 users and 3 domains.</p>
    <p>The pricing models differ structurally. iubenda offers monthly billing with transparent tier progression, while Termly locks you into annual contracts. Osano combines a published entry price with custom enterprise quotes for mid-tier and advanced plans.</p>

    <h3>Free Plan Inclusions</h3>
    <p>iubenda's free plan includes a basic cookie banner and privacy policy generator for sites with limited traffic. The consent solution operates without branding removal or advanced customization, suitable for personal projects or pre-launch websites.</p>
    <p>Termly provides a free tier that covers basic privacy policy generation and cookie scanning for small sites. The plan includes watermarked consent banners and limited document customization.</p>
    <p>Osano offers a free plan focused on foundational cookie consent and basic privacy policy tools. Like competitors, the free version includes branding and restricts advanced features such as geo-targeting and consent analytics.</p>

    <h3>Paid Plans and Upgrades</h3>
    <p>iubenda's paid tiers progress from €4.99/month to €19.99/month (50K pageviews with complete legal documents and geo-targeting) to €79.99/month (150K pageviews with advanced documents, Mobile SDK, and white-labeling). Each tier removes specific limitations rather than gating entire feature categories.</p>
    <p>Termly's paid plans scale based on pageview volume and feature depth, with costs increasing substantially for businesses needing multi-language support or advanced compliance automation. Annual billing remains mandatory across paid tiers.</p>
    <p>Osano's progression moves from the $199/month entry point directly to custom enterprise pricing. Mid-sized businesses fall into a quote-based pricing gap between the starter tier and full enterprise packages, making budgeting less predictable than with published tier structures.</p>

    <h2>Risk Management, Monitoring, and Integrations</h2>

    <p>Each platform approaches compliance monitoring differently, with varying levels of vendor risk assessment and user preference management. iubenda and Osano provide more comprehensive ROPA capabilities, while Termly focuses on streamlined document generation with basic monitoring features.</p>

    <h3>Compliance Monitoring</h3>
    <p>Osano offers the most robust compliance monitoring system among the three platforms. It provides continuous scanning of your website to detect changes in tracking technologies and third-party services. The system automatically alerts you when new cookies or scripts are added that could affect compliance.</p>
    <p>iubenda includes compliance monitoring through its scanner tool, which checks your website for cookies and generates reports on tracking activities. You can schedule regular scans to maintain awareness of your compliance status. The platform updates your consent solution automatically when new tracking technologies are detected.</p>
    <p>Termly provides basic compliance monitoring with its cookie scanner that identifies tracking technologies on your site. The tool runs periodic scans and notifies you of changes, though the monitoring is less comprehensive than Osano's real-time approach. You'll need to manually review and update policies based on scan results.</p>

    <h3>Vendor Risk and ROPA</h3>
    <p>Osano stands out with its vendor risk management capabilities and ROPA (Record of Processing Activities) functionality. The platform maintains a database of third-party vendors and their data processing activities, automatically populating your ROPA based on technologies detected on your site. You can track data flows, processing purposes, and legal bases for each vendor.</p>
    <p>iubenda offers ROPA generation as part of its higher-tier plans, allowing you to document processing activities and generate required records for GDPR compliance. The system connects your privacy policy selections to ROPA entries, reducing duplicate work.</p>
    <p>Termly provides basic ROPA templates but lacks the automated vendor risk assessment features found in Osano. You'll need to manually maintain records of processing activities and vendor relationships.</p>

    <h3>Dashboards and Preference Centers</h3>
    <p>All three platforms offer consent dashboards, but with different capabilities. Osano provides a centralized dashboard showing consent rates, user preferences, and compliance metrics across multiple properties. The preference center allows visitors to manage their consent choices granularly, including options for withdrawing consent and accessing data subject rights.</p>
    <p>iubenda's preference center integrates with its consent solution, giving users control over cookie categories and individual services. The dashboard displays consent statistics and helps you demonstrate compliance to regulators.</p>
    <p>Termly includes a basic preference center where users can modify their cookie settings. The dashboard shows consent acceptance rates and policy view metrics, though it offers fewer analytics than Osano's enterprise-focused reporting. Termly does not currently offer dedicated whistleblowing management features, unlike some enterprise compliance platforms.</p>

    <h2>Support, Reviews, and Market Feedback</h2>

    <h3>Customer Support Quality</h3>
    <p>iubenda provides email support and maintains an extensive knowledge base with detailed documentation. You can access priority support on higher-tier plans, though live chat is not available on all pricing levels.</p>
    <p>Termly offers email support along with a help center containing guides and tutorials. The platform focuses on self-service resources, which works well for straightforward compliance needs but may require patience for complex issues.</p>
    <p>Osano provides tiered support based on your subscription level. Enterprise customers receive dedicated account management and priority assistance. The platform includes a support portal and email-based ticketing system for handling technical questions.</p>

    <h3>User Reviews and Insights</h3>
    <p>According to recent comparison data, iubenda holds a rating of 8.6/10 among free compliance tools, making it the highest-rated option in that category. Termly follows closely with an 8.4/10 rating, while Osano receives an 8.5/10 score.</p>
    <p>Users praise iubenda for its global privacy compliance capabilities and comprehensive legal document generation. Termly receives positive feedback for its budget-friendly pricing and straightforward interface, particularly among small businesses and freelancers. Osano users highlight the platform's robust features and enterprise scalability.</p>

    <h2>Advanced and Specialized Compliance Tools</h2>

    <h3>Google Consent Mode v2</h3>
    <p>Termly and iubenda both offer full support for Google Consent Mode v2, which allows your website to adjust how Google tags behave based on user consent choices. This means Google Analytics and Google Ads can still collect aggregated data while respecting user privacy preferences.</p>
    <p>iubenda is a <strong>Google-certified CMP</strong> with IAB validation, giving you verified compliance when running ads in the EU. The platform automatically maps first-party cookies and integrates directly with Google Tag Manager for seamless consent signal transmission.</p>
    <p>Termly also supports Google Consent Mode v2 and provides cookie blocking capabilities that prevent tags from firing until users grant permission. The implementation works across all major website platforms without requiring custom code.</p>
    <p>Osano doesn't emphasize Google Consent Mode v2 as prominently in its feature set. The platform focuses more on vendor risk management and cross-regulation compliance rather than specific ad-tech integrations.</p>

    <h3>HIPAA and Data Subject Requests</h3>
    <p>None of these three platforms are designed as primary HIPAA compliance solutions, since HIPAA requires technical safeguards that go beyond consent management. You'll need dedicated healthcare compliance tools if you handle protected health information.</p>
    <p>All three platforms do handle Data Subject Access Requests (DSARs) effectively. iubenda provides a centralized dashboard where you can manage access, deletion, and portability requests from users exercising their privacy rights. Termly includes DSAR tools in its Pro+ plan. Osano offers the most comprehensive DSAR automation, tracking request status and automating workflows to ensure you meet regulatory deadlines.</p>
    <p>Osano stands out with automated vendor risk monitoring that helps you assess third-party processors handling user data. This becomes critical when managing DSAR requests that span multiple systems and service providers.</p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details class="faq-item" open>
      <summary>Which platform offers the most comprehensive GDPR and CCPA compliance features for a growing business?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>iubenda delivers strong GDPR coverage with detailed clause libraries tailored to European data protection requirements and multi-language support across ten languages. The platform has been refined specifically for EU markets since 2011. CCPA coverage exists but remains less comprehensive than its European counterparts.</p>
        <p>Termly focuses primarily on US regulations including CCPA and CPRA with robust support for American privacy frameworks. GDPR compliance is available but lacks the depth of European-native platforms.</p>
        <p>Osano positions itself as an enterprise-grade solution with broad regulatory coverage spanning GDPR, CCPA, LGPD, PIPEDA, and additional frameworks. The platform targets mid-market and enterprise customers needing multi-jurisdiction support.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How do the pricing models compare across plans, add-ons, and pageview or domain limits?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>iubenda charges annual subscriptions starting around €29 for basic privacy and cookie policies on a single site. The Ultra plan at approximately €99 annually adds terms of use and sale generators. Each additional website requires a separate subscription.</p>
        <p>Termly offers a free tier with branded policies for one website and up to 100,000 monthly page views. Premium plans start at roughly $15 monthly or $170 annually, removing branding and expanding pageview limits.</p>
        <p>Osano uses enterprise pricing that is not publicly listed and requires sales conversations. Costs generally exceed both iubenda and Termly but include advanced privacy operations tools, dedicated account management, and compliance workflow features designed for teams.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Which solution provides the strongest consent management capabilities, including IAB TCF support and GPC handling?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>iubenda provides a consent management platform with built-in consent logging and a registry that stores proof of user preferences. IAB Transparency and Consent Framework support is available on higher-tier plans.</p>
        <p>Termly includes consent management with automatic cookie scanning and user preference centers. The platform supports IAB TCF 2.2 on business plans and treats GPC signals as valid opt-out mechanisms under California law.</p>
        <p>Osano offers a full-featured consent manager with granular controls for purposes, vendors, and IAB TCF compliance built into standard plans. GPC signal handling is automatic and configurable, with advanced preference management including cross-device sync and consent withdrawal workflows.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How easy is it to implement and customize cookie banners, privacy policies, and preference centers without developer support?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>iubenda requires some technical configuration but provides plugins for WordPress, Shopify, and major CMS platforms that simplify deployment. The visual banner designer allows color and position customization.</p>
        <p>Termly delivers the most accessible no-code experience among the three platforms. Automated cookie scanning identifies trackers, and the banner builder uses drag-and-drop controls. Non-technical users typically complete setup in under an hour.</p>
        <p>Osano assumes moderate technical literacy with implementation requiring tag manager deployment or direct script installation. The interface targets compliance teams rather than solo entrepreneurs.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What level of automation and monitoring is available for cookie scanning, policy updates, and compliance reporting?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>iubenda offers periodic cookie scanning on paid plans but does not run continuous automated scans. Policy updates happen when you modify your business practices through the generator. The platform sends email alerts for major legal updates.</p>
        <p>Termly provides automatic cookie scanning that runs on schedules you define, detecting new trackers and flagging unclassified cookies. Compliance monitoring includes basic reports showing consent rates and user preferences over time.</p>
        <p>Osano includes continuous cookie scanning with real-time detection of new tracking technologies. Compliance dashboards track consent metrics, data subject requests, vendor assessments, and regulatory deadlines. Automated reporting generates audit-ready documentation for privacy impact assessments and regulatory filings.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How do the integrations and tag manager compatibility differ for common marketing and analytics stacks?</summary>
      <div>
        <p>iubenda integrates directly with Google Tag Manager, allowing automatic blocking of tags until consent is granted. Native connections exist for Google Analytics, Facebook Pixel, and major advertising platforms. WordPress, Joomla, and Shopify plugins handle common CMS environments.</p>
        <p>Termly supports Google Tag Manager and provides template tags for popular analytics and marketing tools. Direct integrations include Shopify, WordPress, Wix, and Squarespace. Custom integrations require JavaScript knowledge.</p>
        <p>Osano offers the broadest integration ecosystem with pre-built connectors for enterprise marketing stacks including Salesforce, Marketo, Adobe Analytics, and segment.io. Tag manager compatibility extends to Google, Tealium, and Adobe Launch. API access enables custom integrations with internal systems and privacy workflow tools.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

